AttackFlow Code Analysis Report


GrayLog

Executive Summary

Why Does the Secure Software Matter?

Software is a complex piece of technology in the very heart of our lives from health to entertainment, from finance to connectivity. No doubt, security should be an integral part of this technology. As the history incessantly reveals malicious intentions against services are not new and software open to whole Internet usage is not an exception. Software products are constant and increasing targets for activists, organized or unorganized hackers, script kiddies, bug hunters and even the governments. The cost here is massive; bad reputation, losing the customer base, money and time.

What are the Approaches to Software Security?

Writing rock solid code is hard. As the requirements evolve and get complex, software divaricates. Ensuring the code written is secure becomes extremely difficult, let alone the code produced works as intended. Producing secure software requires many security related actions to be taken. These actions are but not limited to;

  • Determining security requirements
  • Including security cases along with the use cases
  • Producing threat models
  • Executing code analysis
  • Running dynamic security tests (penetration tests)

What is Security Static Code Analysis?

A phenomenon that every software security expert agrees upon is that in the software life cycle the early the bugs are found, the logarithmically less cost they induce. One of most important and somewhat widely adopted software security action is the security static code analysis, which can be defined as the tests automatically executed on the non-running code with a security-centric perspective focusing on finding weaknesses. One of the biggest advantages of static code analysis is that the process can be fulfilled early and repetitively.

Whats the Action Plan?

Theres a major amount of work to be done for security software production. These work can be classified into long-term, mid-term and short-term actions that can be taken towards semi-scientific but measurable secure software development process.

Short-Term Actions

Not every weaknesses carries the same risk against the software. With lack of time and other resources, the prioritization is the key for successful risk mitigation. Therefore, critical findings should be analyzed and immediately be pushed into a bugfix cycle for the short-term.

Mid-Term Actions

According to the categories of findings, focusing more on problematic areas will provide scope-aware actions. Increasing the awareness and preparing the validation processes (custom rules for static analysis, specialized peer-reviews, trainings) on these areas will help towards a secure software tailored to your company.

There are nine classes of findings that AttackFlow produces including but not limited to input validation, cryptography, authorization, configuration, etc.

Categories Actions
Configuration
  • Increase configurational security awareness of application server administrators
  • Prepare and enforce configuration hardening processes when the software hits the production servers
Cryptography
  • Increase the software cryptography awareness (generic cryptography topics to choosing sound algorithms and using these algorithms in targeted programming frameworks in real-life) of all developers, application server administrators and analysts
  • Prepare and enforce cryptography standards that should be used through-out the developers
Authentication, Authorization
  • Increase the authentication awareness of developers and analysts including authentication methods and using corresponding APIs in the targeted frameworks
  • Prepare and enforce authentication methods that should be used throughout the software ecosystem
  • Run a review, manual inspection by security savvy developers or security experts on code specifically implemented for authorization
Session Management, Web 2.0
  • Increase the HTTP knowledge awareness of developers and testers focusing on the network traffic and how the attackers manipulate the data
  • Increase the security related Web 2.0 knowledge for emerging technologies for developers keen on using/implementing them in a secure fashion
Miscellaneous
  • Choose appropriate developers with security ambition for each team , reserving appropriate time on researching software security issues, best practices on the targeted software and sharing the findings with the team weekly
Code Quality
  • Prepare and enforce a tailored code quality standards that should be used throughout the software ecosystem by the developers
Input Validation
  • Research on and apply secure way of outputting data to customers in the views using targeted framework APIs and 3rd party libraries if targeted frameworks fall short
  • Prepare and enforce a solid not only an input validation and but, and more importantly output encoding methodologies that should be used throughout the software ecosystem by the developers.

Long-Term Actions

Maturity models have been increasingly used for producing secure softwares. There are more than one software security maturity models that plan, detail and formalize security actions for software life cycles. According to these maturity models there are many venues that must be visited with many levels for a process to produce a software whose security can be measured. One such open source and popular maturity model is OpenSAMM.

OpenSAMM formalizes most of the mid-term action items and distributes them to levels of maturities. Therefore, it is possible to measure the effects of security actions taken and comparing them to other teams, projects, departments and even companies.

Specifically maturity models include security actions including but not limited to;

  • Governance, such as preparing company specific security standards and security trainings
  • Construction, such as preparing security requirements and applying threat modeling on designs
  • Verification, such as security testing, for which this report is a part of and code review
  • Deployment, such as finding management and configurational hardening

However, without an application security specialist dedicated to software security the implementation of the maturity model may fail. Therefore, an important prerequisite to for long-term actions, dedicated application software security specialist(s) whose sole responsibilities include the implementation of a software security maturity model should be present.

Vulnerability Categories

Empty Catch Block

Low

Swallowing exceptions may result in hackers go unnoticed when they send unexpected requests to a target application.

Description

Modern high-level language compilers are particularly picky about empty catch blocks since these style of coding usually points to bad quality code.

We, developers, usually suppress these compiler warnings with code such as below; 

                        
try
{
    String wholeFile = FileUtils.readFileToString(path);
}
catch(IOException ioe)
{
    // happy compiler
   string happyCompiler = ioe.getMessage();
}


However, making any exception go unnoticed may help attackers to hide their trials and errors against the application. Additionally suppressing exception in this way will prevent any detail analysis against production problems.

Mitigation

The recommended solution is catching all the relevant exceptions that can be thrown in the try block. This is not enough, however, since all the caught exceptions should be handled properly;

  1. ensuring the state of the program is not in an insecure one
  2. log the exception details
  3. notify application operation teams if the exception is a critical one

Generic Exception Catch Block

Low

Hiding specific exceptions may allow hackers actions go unnoticed when they send unexpected requests to a target application

Description

In order not to think too much about the handling of specific exceptions we, developers, have an inclination towards writing overly broad exception handlers such as below code snippet; 

                        
try
{
    processFile();
}
catch(Exception e)
{
       LOGGER.log(Level.SEVERE, File process exception occurred, e);
}

There are more than one exception that can be thrown at runtime running the above code;

  • FileNotFoundException
  • FileSystemException
  • NotDirectoryException

However, theres only one action when they occur. On the other hand, the fail safe actions that should be taken might differ from exception type to the other.

Thinking on handling and catching specific exceptions might allow us to catch an unusual behaviour and possibly catch a prospective attacker.

Mitigation

An exception throwing code should be handled in detail. Instead of using a generic Exception type, the specific exceptions should be seeked and handled in the code, even the handling code used becomes to be duplicate. This way new exceptions that the changed code introduces will be forced to be handled with care.

Ineffective Catch Block

Low

Exception catch blocks with only logging may result in unstable system or denial of service

Description

When handling an exception in catch blocks, we, developers, usually only log details with code such as below without thinking over what action should be taken further, too much; 

                        
try
{
    String wholeFile = FileUtils.readFileToString(path);
}
catch(IOException ioe)
{
   LOGGER.log(Level.SEVERE, File exception occurred, ioe);
}

Logging is an essential part of an exception handling, however, this is similar to ignoring the problem by without taking certain actions. For example, a resource acquired in the try block should have been released in the same catch block or better yet in a finally block.

Otherwise the resource will be reserved for an indeterminate amount of time, leaving system in possible denial of service situation.

Mitigation

While logging the exception and its details is important, its also important to take further smart actions against the exception such as releasing the locks or resources reserved in the try block right after the exception.

Insecure Logging - System Output Stream

Low

Upon an attack its hard to research on the trails and find evidence against it

Description

Logging is one of the most critical actions that a developer must implement in order to provide a more secure software.

After an attack logs are is the place auditors should look and pinpoint the root of the vulnerability and any source of the attackers.


There are many more ways of logging; logging to database, filesystem, registry, events and the console. Logging to console will make the auditing part harder since its not structured and persistent. 

                            
System.out.println("ERROR: " +  npe.getMessage());

Mitigation

Any logging attempt using System.out should be replaced with one of the more stable, flexible and structured mechanism such as log4j.

Low

Sensitive data or internal sensitive information leading to vulnerabilities may leak through code comments

Description

Comments are the key mechanism in order to make easier for a human to read a code and understand its goal, tricks etc.

Since comments can be rich, sometimes, we, developers put far more information than we should put and then forget all about it. These comments may also indicate potential vulnerabilities if they fall into the hands of malicious parties.

Suspicious comments should be analyzed in order not to contain sensitive information such as hacks, default credentials, backdoors and etc.

Leftover Debug Code

Medium

Debugging code left on the application may give attackers the extra information they need for attacking the target

Description

Generally in a web application debugging code may present itself in different forms. One of these forms is the main method; 

                        
public static void main(String[] args) {
{
  //...
}


The above is unnecessary for a web application and may contain critical security bugs and since they are outside the scope of a regular penetration testing (a form of dynamic security testing), the flow may give an attacker an unnecessary and unexpected advantage.

Similar example would be a URL parameter when set will bypass controls at the server side, for example; 

                            
http://www.vulnerable.com/Account/Authenticate?token=...&debug=1


The above URL, without the debug parameter, will check the tokens validity and authenticates the request. But if the developer placed a kind of a backdoor that bypasses the authentication, for just purposes perhaps, in terms of a debug parameter, then the same will hold for an attacker, too. By presenting a debug=1 parameter, he/she will authenticate without a valid token.

Mitigation

Unnecessary entrance points in terms of any debugging code should not be left in the production code.

  • CWE-489

Hardcoded Password

High

Hardcoded passwords are prohibited by various security standards, but also a bad practice since a successful hack attempt can be used against developers knowing the production passwords

Description

Its very attractive to keep a service accounts password in the code. Because this method of storing seems to be very convenient and simple. However, there are a substantial amount of standards (such as PCI-DSS, HIPAA, SOX etc.) that have put rules against this style of coding. Moreover, its in fact hard to maintain a password this way since the password might change or locked, as such needs maintenance.

Additionally, if a hacker somehow successfully gathers a piece of the code, he will eventually get the hardcoded password. GitHub is full of software projects with hardcoded passwords stored in the code.

Mitigation

Dont put credentials such as service users passwords in the code. There are security standards to be in compliant that prohibit this. Moreover, for worse, as a developer we dont want to be accused of a successful hack just because we know a production password.

Once this decision is being made, the question arises; where should we keep the passwords and more importantly how should we keep them safely? Unlike .NET DPAPI, Java doesnt provide an internal, transparent and easy way of encryption/decryption method. However there is a wrapper around Microsoft DPAPI, JDPAPI, for Java platforms on Windows systems.

In cryptography, managing keys is a very hard topic to tackle with. Most of the time when storing the key protecting passwords on web server, application server, directory server or database server is not considered to be safe and compliant, Hardware Security Modules (HSM) are advised to manage application keys whenever required and appropriate.

However, storing passwords that protects encryption keys in permission-restricted and constantly monitored files, database tables should be enough most of the cases.

References

  • CWE-259
  • CWE-798
  • CWE-321
  • HIPAA Security Rule 45 CFR 164.308(a)(5)(ii)(D)
  • HIPAA Security Rule 45 CFR 164.312(a)(2)(iv)
  • HIPAA Security Rule 45 CFR 164.312(e)(2)(ii)
  • OWASP Top 10 A6
  • PCI DSS 6.5.3

Insecure Random Number Generator

High

The attacker can predict the next generated value before the algorithm produces one

Description

Producing random values is a usual requirement for software projects. Theres no real but pseudo-randomness in computers. Unfortunately pseudorandomness is deterministic (related the computers) and therefore reproducible.

The random (although pseudo) number generator algorithms are usually used to produce secret keys for encryption algorithms. However, they are also used to identify users, such as session cookies, produce SMS OTPs, random file names, etc.

Using insecure random number generator algorithms we, as developers, make the lives of attackers easier. The code below uses an insecure random number generator and produced random 8 character strings can be predicted by an attacker. 

                            
String symbols = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRYZabcdefghijklmwxyz0123456789";
Random random = new Random();
char[] buffer = new char[8];
for (int i = 0; i < buffer.length;="" ++i)="" {="" buffer[i]="symbols.charAt[random.nextInt(symbols.length())];" }="" string="" randomstring="new" string(buf);="">

Mitigation

The best we can do is to use cryptographically secure pseudo random number generators provided by the framework.

In order to use a secure version of Random, java.security.SecureRandom should be used. 

                            
String symbols = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRYZabcdefghijklmwxyz0123456789";
SecureRandom random = SecureRandom.getInstanceStrong();
char[] buffer = new char[8];
for (int i = 0; i < buffer.length;="" ++i)="" {="" buffer[i]="symbols.charAt[random.nextInt(symbols.length())];" }="" string="" randomstring="new" string(buf);="">

References

  • CWE-338
  • HIPAA Security Rule 45 CFR 164.312(a)(2)(i)
  • HIPAA Security Rule 45 CFR 164.312(a)(2)(iv)
  • HIPAA Security Rule 45 CFR 164.312(e)(2)(ii)
  • OWASP Top 10 A6
  • PCI DSS 6.5.3

Use of Dangerous Regular Expressions

High

The attacker can force application into a denial of service state

Description

Regular expressions are very useful when finding patterns in strings. The technique is also extensively used for security when finding bad user input or accept them in only expected format, which is by the way, by far more secure than the first.

On the other hand, regular expressions can be quite complex and the engine that runs them should be as efficient as possible. However, it is this complexity that can sometimes produce denial of service opportunities for attackers.

For example, the code snippet below can take 17 seconds to complete in a decent computer, not to mention %100 CPU; 

                        
String pattern = "^(([a-z])+.)+[A-Z]([a-z])+$";
String input = "aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa!";
System.out.println(input.matches(pattern));

This long computing sessions are due to the repetitive/cascading groupings used in the regular expression patterns.

Mitigation

When using regular expression patterns repetitions in groupings may create denial of service problems. Theres no definitive answer for whether a regular expression will be the root reason of denial of service in an application framework, however, as a general rule when creating pattern you can follow below rules;


  • Avoid to use patterns that can imply each other, such as using question mark, as in aa and aaa?
  • Avoid repetitive/cascading groups, as in (a+)+

A custom timeout infrastructure can also be implemented that throws exceptions when a timeout period passes evaluating a regular expression as in stackoverflow answer.

References

  • CWE-185
  • HIPAA Security Rule 45 CFR 164.308(a)(5)(ii)(B)
